    <item>
      <title>Re: Do the gods have limits to their influence on Norrath?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Lore&amp;message.id=11267#M11267</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I would like to point out that in Kithicor, Innoruuk did not get up and go of his own volition.&amp;nbsp; He was summoned there by Laarthik K'Shin using the Blue Orb.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Furthermore, I believe a god's ability to directly affect mortals is likewise directly affected by that mortal's worship of the deity.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The more people worship a deity, they more he is able to impact that society or culture directly.&amp;nbsp; If an entire culture refuses to worship Innoruuk, he's not able to "get into their hearts and souls" per se - but likewise, they are unable to receive his blessings.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Thus he could not simply "lay waste" to the elves without messing with the world, and while Innoruuk and Tunare may dislike one another, one needs to accept that the gods are responsible enough not to constantly up mountains, dry rivers, or unleash immolations every time they have a quibble with a god.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;So fine, Innoruuk hates Tunare: Why risk such long standing negative consequences by constantly playing with the world's terrain?&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;It's kind of like nuclear war: the option is always available, but the situation needs to be rather dire to use it.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Besides, were there any widespread Solusek Ro worshippers prior to his creation of the Desert?&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;And finally, if Tunare is a "Good" deity, why would she lead a reprisal against Solusek's followers, and not just Solusek himelf?&lt;/P&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by Ezedriel on &lt;span class=date_text&gt;06-01-2006&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=time_text&gt;04:29 AM&lt;/span&gt;</description>
